t of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Flete","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: nickname or metonymic occupational name from <i>flete</i> ‘freight, charter (fee)’. This surname is most common in the Dominican Republic."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Flete was born about 1150, in Fleet, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Josce de Flete, was 24 and his mother, Adelais de Comps, was 27. He married Julian de Moulton. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1217, in his hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1150–1217":"umbes 1150–1217","1150–1217":"1150–1217","1175–1217":"1175–1217","1127–1217":"1127–1217","1125–1188":"1125–1188","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1188":"1188","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Roquevaire, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Roquevaire, Bouches-du-Rhône, Prantsusmaa","Fleet, Lincolnshire, England":"Fleet, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1150–1217":"noin 1150–1217","1150–1217":"1150–1217","1175–1217":"1175–1217","1127–1217":"1127–1217","1125–1188":"1125–1188","about 1150":"noin 1150","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1188":"1188","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1175":"noin 1175","Roquevaire, Bouches-du-Rhône, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur, France":"Roquevaire, Bouches-du-Rhône, Ranska","Fleet, Lincolnshire, England":"Fleet, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1150–1217":"environ 1150–1217","1150–1217":"1150–1217","1175–1217":"1175–1217","1127–1217":"1127–1217","1125–1188":"1125–1188","about 1150":"en